The Sultan's Palace is the failed keystone of a political experiment: unifying oasis water-law, desert charter governance, and pyramid funerary sovereignty under one court.

After the Ninth Meridian catastrophe, Sultan Kheir al-Zafir required caravan charters, household oaths, and funerary declarations registered in a single palace archive.
This standardized witness formats and seal verification but created a single choke point controlling legitimacy.

Three factions collided: Water-Court Pragmatists (measurable quotas), Sultanate Centralists (throne prerogative), Funerary Absolutists (death stewardship above civic law).

The palace adopted Corrective Harmonization: selective rewriting of identity and obligation disguised as reconciling contradictory records.
Families could not prove inheritance. Caravans could not prove toll exemptions. Social order became administratively legible but existentially unstable.

The end: palace centralists attempted a rite to bind aquifer flow to dynastic succession symbols.
Pressure seals ruptured. Archive vaults flooded. Petition courts were cut off from evacuation. Known as the Drowning of the Court.

Kheir al-Zafir reportedly died in the apex sanctum. Court records afterward still bear his seal, implying forged continuity or posthumous governance by ritual mechanism.
The palace ghosts are procedural remains of a civilization that tried to make law, water, memory, and death answer to one throne.
